Hema-Quebec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the establishment and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased because Hema-Quebec became one of the most reliable and inefficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the trust of the public, who was seriously disturbed after a scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980 ’ s and 1990 ’ s.
As is generally known, the State reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Committee was contaminated during the 1980s by an immune deficiency (HIV) and a C-type hepatitis virus.
In view of this drama and the wave of unrest of the public, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation in February 1994 by Judge Horace Krever to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a loss can no longer be recovered.
While Judge Krever left the report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new system of blood management in Canada.
In Quebec, the Géline's committee was set up.
According to the report by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to be owned by Quebec, and the Canadian blood company for the storage of all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Quebec started his activities in 1998, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was overwhelming.
In a consistent effort to increase the safety of blood products and the continued work in this area over the years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that by the beginning of 2008 Hema-Québec had already believed 94% of the Quebec population.
Dr. Décary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is very fragile."
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998 Hema-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
"At that time we witnessed in Europe the presence of many human cases of crazy cow disease, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," the woman, who has been leading the company since her founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread blood.
Therefore, we have relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krever and Gélineau's report, according to which in the event that we do not know, and in the event that there is a serious disease at stake, in this case, the Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which constitutes the degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, must be taken by an exclusive measure.
Thus, in April 1999, we refused to accept blood from people who stayed in the United Kingdom for a period of more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease was transmitted to the blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping the principle of caution made sense."
In 1999 much more accurate HIV detection techniques were found on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that enable the presence of the virus itself directly in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which tests were used previously.
NAT tests have allowed short periods of noise between the patient's infection and the moment our blood technology can be detected, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period for less than a week.
We have thus significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without getting to know it.
This improvement has significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
The risk of getting the blood contaminated by HIV is now exposed to one of the 12 million people.
"In other words, it means that before someone gets HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
In view of this, Hema-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of transmission of HIV through the blood product appears.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion that is necessary for healing," says Head of Hema-Quebek.
"The challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know what pathogen may appear in the system.
Just last year, on the island of Réunion, the Chikungunya virus was found, which, like the West Nile virus, transmits to the blood by stabbing the tissue.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that, in addition to safe storage, Hema-Québec must also be counted with sufficient storage.
"They need to grow, because the population will grow old.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
