Psychology of drudgery: Why are we wasting more money?
At auctions customers are willing to spend more money, to overestimate goods.
The neurological and economic basis of this well-known - and apparently irrational - behavior has been able to reveal to researchers from the field of neurology and economy of New York University.
According to their study published in Science magazine, people don't want to stay in eBay auction competition, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Research using experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers agreed, the other group participated in field auctions, using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) tested the active area of the brain of the pilots.
In both games, participants could win money, however, during the auction game, the important element of which is to block the other side, began to function intensively during the loss of the entire being under the brain core, called the striatum.
This brain area plays in addition to many other functions in the "self-recovery" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, it is possible, according to researchers, to explain how to avoid direct street reactions.
In support of their theory, members of the research team from a number of economies carried out a financial cross-check investigation.
Under different conditions, three groups had been competing against one partner.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product concerned, and they made their commitments.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they quit winning, they would receive $15.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also paid these money.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was based on the fact that one was highlighted by the win and the other loss.
However, the members of the "towards the loss" group were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "victorious" group, which confirms the neurologist's hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena noticeable in auctioning the joys of winning and avoiding the risk.
When neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the dispute between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," noted Andrew Schutter, professor of Economics College of New York University.
Hepatitis: when to look for a doctor?
About half a billion people around the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, although only seven thousand of them are treated, because the patient often does not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is a summary of the name of the infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, there is signs of inflammation of the liver and the liver, however, the cause of the disease and the disease they cause differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the underlying disease: type A and E hepatitis (e.g. food-infected, water), type B, C, D hepatitis and other blood and body fluids (sperm, secretion, saliva).
Travellers should in any case be protected by choking against A and B viruses, and no C vaccine virus exists.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after the use of the infected food, usually due to nausea, weakness, chest problems, vomiting.
Then there is a yellow, bright chair and dark urine on the skin and the eyeballs. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year millions of people around the world die from the more serious type of disease, from liver cancer and from hepatitis B-induced liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only every tenth of the infected medicinal product is treated.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to liver cirrhosis or cancer of the liver.
Most of those infected with their disease don't even know, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells randomly, so the first symptoms are delivered in many cases up to 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, regular testing is very important.
In three groups, this disease occurs more frequently than in the average: between people who had passed blood transfusions before 1991, between drug users and people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated total number of units infected with chronic hepatitis C 200 million is estimated.
Since the disease can show a routine laboratory examination, a person should, in case of any signs of unknown origin, refer to his doctor.
In early detection, the disease is therapeutic, the virus can be removed from the body, preventing such infections and preventing cancer.
On 30 September, the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized by organisations representing the disease, was organized worldwide in 2004.
Its purpose is to warn of the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of their formation and the importance of early detection of the disease.
